  "prompt": "How? Ant walks from corner A (bottom left) of front wall to the other corner C (bottom right) of rear wall of a 3 meter cubical room. Shortest route?",
  "response": "To find the shortest route for an ant walking from corner A (the bottom-left corner of the front wall) to corner C (the bottom-right corner of the rear wall) in a 3-meter cubical room, you can visualize unfolding the cube into a flat plane. \n\nHere is one way to unfold the cube:\n\n1. Unfold the cube so that the front, side, and back walls are laid out in a straight line (essentially forming a single flat rectangle).\n\nIn the flattened plane:\n- The front wall is a 3-meter by 3-meter square where A is at the bottom-left corner.\n- The side wall is adjacent and can be unfolded to the right, creating another 3-meter by 3-meter square.\n- The rear wall is adjacent to the side wall, forming a third square directly to the right.\n\nThe ant's path can now be visualized as a straight line from corner A on the front wall across the 3-meter width to the right side of the unfolded cube (on the back wall where corner C is located). \n\nIf you calculate the diagonal distance from corner A of the unfolded rectangle to corner C, you will find that it forms a 3-meter by 6-meter rectangle. The shortest distance (diagonal) through the flat plane is calculated using the Pythagorean theorem:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Diagonal} = \\sqrt{3^2 + 6^2} = \\sqrt{9 + 36} = \\sqrt{45} = 3\\sqrt{5}\n\\]\n\nThus, the shortest route is \\(3\\sqrt{5}\\) meters.",
